lead_paragraph:
BURNS--George Edward,

86, died September 23, 2015, of complications from Alzheimer's Disease. Born in Scranton, grew up in Washington, DC, graduated from Georgetown, finally settling in NYC in the 60's. He had a varied career with AAA, Pan Am, TWA, and Citibank. He was active in Civil Air Patrol, Overseas Press Club, and the Iron Gate Chapter of the Air Force Association. He is survived by his wife Barbara. There will be a wake from 6-9pm at Riverside Memorial Chapel on Monday evening the 28th, with a Vigil Service of sung evening vespers and remembrances at 7:30pm. A funeral mass will be held at Holy Name of Jesus Church (96th and Amsterdam) at 10:30am on Tuesday, September 29th. Burial will take place at Mt. Olivet Cemetery in Washington, DC, on Thursday morning at 11:30. A full obituary is on the Riverside Memorial Chapel website.

lead_paragraph: BING--Alexander III "Sandy," 84, passed away at home after a sudden, brief fight with lung cancer on September 12, 2015. Sandy was born and lived in New York City; attended Dalton and Lincoln Schools, graduated Phi Beta Kappa from Middlebury College and received a Masters degree in American History from Columbia University; served in Europe after WWII in the United States Army. Sandy was a partner and Director of Research at L.F. Rothschild, and later worked at Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette in fixed income research. He married Cynthia Eaton, and together they raised four children. Sandy's parents, Matilda S. and Alexander S. Bing; wife, Cynthia E. Bing; daughter, Abigail R. Bing; and former wife, Elisabeth G. Bing predeceased him. He is survived by son, Alexander M. Bing; daughters, Cynthia K. Bing and Virginia G. Bing; son-in-law, Michael Padial; and granddaughter, Eloise B. Padial. A memorial service will be held at The Church of the Heavenly Rest, 90th St. and 5th Ave. at 3pm, October 16, 2015 with reception to follow. In lieu of flowers, please make donations to Friends of the Upper Delaware River (FUDR.org) and/or EarlySteps.org. To view full obituary, visit: www.legacy.com. 1/3

lead_paragraph: FRICK--Alix (Halperin) Nelson, age 77, of Nantucket and New York City, died peacefully at the Sherborn, MA home of her daughter. Mrs. Nelson-Frick was a renowned author, book editor and advertising executive. Retired CEO of the New York advertising agency, Franklin Spier, Inc., she grew up in Manhattan, the daughter of legendary advertising copywriter Shirley Polykoff. Alix contributed reviews and articles to The New York Times Book Review, Newsday and women's magazines. Among her publications, she authored Amazon Best Sellers "The Stuff of Legend - A Daughter's Take on the Woman Who Transformed Advertising in the 1960's" and "My Inner India - Unraveling While Traveling from Delhi to Mumbai." Her recent book, "Hilarity - the Arc of a Life," takes stock with grace and humor of a life well-lived. She continued her thoughts and musings on her popular blog, "Hilarity," at AlixFrick.com until her passing. Wife of the Late Robert W. Frick, she and her husband spent their retirement years living on Nantucket and traveling throughout the world. She is survived by her daughter, Shawn Nelson Laughlin and her husband Buz of Sherborn, and her daughter, Corin Nelson of Santa Monica, CA; her stepdaughter, Amy L. Frick of New York City; and three grandchildren, Adden Laughlin and Phoebe Laughlin of New York City, and Gus Laughlin of Sherborn. In lieu of flowers, gifts in memory of Mrs. Alix Nelson-Frick may be made in support of the Pancreatic Cancer Research efforts of Mass General Hospital. Checks may be made out to Massachusetts General Hospital c/o Development Office, Attn: Mary McQuillen, 125 Nashua Street, Suite 540, Boston, MA 02114. Gifts online may be made at: www.giving.massgeneral.org.For the guest book and obituary, please visit: www.everettfuneral.com. 1/3

lead_paragraph: THOMPSON--Norman. Norman Winslow Thompson, M.D., PhD, (Hon., Linkoping University), FACS, FRACS (Hon.), FRCPSG (Hon.) Dr. Norman Winslow Thompson, a pioneer in endocrine surgery, died peacefully at home surrounded by members of his family on Tuesday, November 17th in Ann Arbor, Michigan at the age of 83. Dr. Thompson had a long and distinguished career in medicine and trained, mentored and influenced generations of surgeons around the world. He was born in Boston, MA, in 1932. He received his B.A. degree from Hope College in 1953 and his M.D. degree from the University of Michigan Medical School in Ann Arbor in 1957. He was appointed to the faculty of University of Michigan as Instructor in 1962. He advanced to a full Professor in 1971. He was subsequently appointed the first Henry King Ransom Endowed Professor of Surgery in 1979 for the duration of his academic career. Dr. Thompson was an active, participating and founding member of many professional organizations and received numerous awards including an honorary PhD from the University of Linkoping, Sweden. Dr. Thompson was a beloved teacher of surgery at the University of Michigan and helped to train over 265 chief residents in surgery. He was appointed Professor Emeritus of Surgery on his retirement in 2001. The University of Michigan has established both an endowed Professorship and a Fellowship of Endocrine Surgery in Dr. Thompson's name. Dr. Thompson is survived by his wife of 59 years, Marcia Veldman Thompson; son Robert W. Thompson, and daughters Karen L. Thompson, Susan M. Thompson-Doering and Jennifer E. Thompson McGuffin. He leaves behind five grandchildren and three step- grandchildren. A memorial gathering is being planned at a later date. In lieu of flowers, the family requests that contributions be made to Hope College, the University of Michigan Division of Endocrine Surgery, or the American Association of Endocrine Surgeons (AAES) Foundation. Please feel free to visit: www.niefuneralhomes.com to search for Dr. Thompson's name to leave messages for the family or view the expanded obituary. 1/3

lead_paragraph: DAVENPORT--William Kirk. William "Bill" Kirk Davenport (1928-2015) died peacefully at his home in Bloomfield Hills, Michigan on September 29, 2015. He was 86. The cause was lung cancer. Bill was born in Jackson, Michigan on December 22, 1928. He graduated from Cranbrook School in 1946, Harvard College in 1950 and the University of Michigan Law School in 1953. After law school, he worked as an associate lawyer at Cravath, Swaine & Moore, a law firm in New York City, until 1962. His time at Cravath was interrupted for three and a half years when he served at the Pentagon in the Army Judge Advocate General's Corps as a 1st Lieutenant. In 1962, he moved from New York back to Michigan to work as a lawyer for Ford Motor Company. He retired from Ford as Assistant General Counsel in 1990. Bill was fortunate to have married Gertrude Baldwin Perkins "Kitty", one of the fabulous identical Perkins Twins of Wilkes-Barre, PA. He was married to Kitty for 47 years until her death in 2006. He also outlived his younger sister, Jean Davenport Crawford, who died in 2002. Bill had a wonderful life. Those who knew him will remember his intelligence, charm, sense of humor and strong moral character, all of which are captured in his daughter Nina Davenport's HBO documentary "First Comes Love" (premiering on Netflix in November). Bill loved his time at Cranbrook, Harvard, and Michigan Law School. He spent his summers at his cottage in the Chicago Club of Charlevoix, Michigan where he had a close community of friends. After retirement, he and Kitty also rented a house every spring in Provence. Bill's favorite sports were cooking, 19th century English literature, vegetable gardening and the New York Times. After his wife Kitty died, he became an avid bridge player. He will be missed by his many bridge partners. Above all, he was a loving and devoted husband and father. Bill is survived by his three children, Kirk, Tim and Nina Davenport, and seven grandchildren: Lydia, Addison, Alexander, Eliza, Jackson, Lucas and Jasper. A memorial service in Bloomfield Hills is being planned for the weekend of November 14, 2015. In lieu of flowers, the family asks that you consider a gift to The Davenport Family Scholarship Fund at the University of Michigan Law School, 701 S. State St., Ann Arbor, MI, 48109-3091. View obituary and share memories at: AJDesmond.com 1/3
